(18, 62, 'Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engine', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nThe Carl Benz School of Engineering offers high school graduates the unique opportunity to study internationally renowned German engineering in English. The 3-year bachelor\'s program aims to prepare future engineers for a successful career.\r\n\r\nThe Bachelor of Science (B.Sc.) program in Mechanical Engineering (International) at Carl Benz School is completed over a period of 3 years (6 semesters). The program begins with a so-called Pre-Semester, a preparatory course in Mathematics, Physics, Chemistry, and English. After two years of intermediate studies, which cover the basic concepts of mechanical engineering, the students can choose to specialize in either Automotive Engineering, Energy Engineering or Global Production Management. Carl Benz School students will graduate with a Bachelor of Science degree from KIT. The Bachelor program organizes lectures, tutorials, and lab courses with lecturers and tutors coming from different institutions of the KIT. This ensures that the quality of the subjects taught to meet the highest standards.\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nCarl Benz School of Engineering\r\nStudy options\r\nFull Time (3 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\n€ 17,307.37 (US $ 19,592) per year\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\n14 October 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nNorth Campus\r\n\r\nHermann-von-Helmholtz-Platz 1 Eggenstein,\r\n\r\nKARLSRUHE,\r\n\r\nBaden Wurttemberg,\r\n\r\n76344, Germany\r\nFull Time (3 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\n€ 17,307.37 (US $ 19,592) per year\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\n14 October 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nKarlsruhe Institute of Technology\r\n\r\nSouth Campus,\r\n\r\nKaiserstraße 12,\r\n\r\nKARLSRUHE,\r\n\r\nBaden Wurttemberg,\r\n\r\n76131, Germany\r\nShow more +\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nApplicants must have the secondary school education at a level equivalent to the German \'Abitur\' (German university entrance qualification). Other English Language Requirements: The TOEFL test (> 230 points for computer based test or> 570 points for paper based test; the UNIcert.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nApplicants have to complete High School Degree.\r\n\r\nTOEFL test (> 230 points for computer based test or> 570 points for paper based test or 88 points for internet based test), Egypt\r\n\r\nIELTS (> 6,5)'),
(19, 63, 'Master of Arts in American Studies', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nProgram Overview\r\n\r\nInside Knowledge with an Outside Perspective\r\n\r\nThe Master of Arts in American Studies (MAS) is an exclusive, interdisciplinary program taught in English and aimed at qualified graduate students from around the world. The MAS is a three semester program, however, a performance-related fast track option (two semesters) is available. American Studies in the MAS is defined by exemplary and interdisciplinary teaching of cultural knowledge about the United States of America. The program provides training in academic and practical skills tailor to meet the needs of future leaders in a transatlantic and global environment. Curriculum include a selection of courses from economics, geography, history, law, literature, musicology, philosophy, political science, religious studies, and sociology.\r\n\r\nProgram Structure\r\n\r\nAmerican Studies at the Heidelberg Center for American Studies is defined as exemplary and interdisciplinary teaching of cultural knowledge about the United States of America in subjects such as American literature, economics, geography, history, art history, law, musicology, political science, philosophy, sociology, and theology / religious studies.\r\n\r\nThe MAS is a three semester program starting each winter semester. Students earn 90 European Credit Transfer System (ECTS) points during the course of the program:\r\n\r\nFirst winter semester (late September to end of January):\r\n\r\nStarts with a one week orientation period followed by a weekly curriculum of 4 subject courses, 2 tutorials, 1 colloquium, and 2 additional courses. Students have to take 4 oral exams during the first week of February.\r\n\r\nWinter break (February and March): During the lecture-free period students are expected to write and hand in 2 to 3 research papers.\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Philosophy\r\nStudy options\r\nFull time (3 semesters)\r\nRegistration fees\r\n€ 3,000.00 (US $ 3,396) annually\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nExpected September 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nUniversity of Heidelberg\r\n\r\nSeminarstraße 2,\r\n\r\nHEIDELBERG,\r\n\r\nBaden Wurttemberg,\r\n\r\n69117, Germany\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents must have a Bachelor degree involving at least 4 years of full-time academic education.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nTo apply for the MAS, you should have earned a university degree of a minimum of four years of studies and - if English is not your native language - be able to present an international, standardized test of English as a foreign language (eg IELTS, TOEFL).\r\n\r\nApplicants who native language is English, it is sufficient Proof that you have your university entrance qualification in one of the have acquainted these countries; Egypt - the certificate of a maximum of two years ago internationally recognized standardized English tests, eg. IELTS with one Overall grade of at least 7.0 points and at least 6.5 Each points in each subcategory, TOEFL IBT with one Score of at least 90 points and at least 22 Each point in each score of at least 185 points on the Cambridge English Scale'),
(19, 64, 'Master of Arts in Anthropology', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nCourse outline\r\n\r\nThis M.A. course enables students to choose from a number of thematic and regional subject emphases. It is noticeable for the way it combines basic research of a theoretical and thematic nature with more practically oriented approaches. The subject matter is the investigation of cultural difference at both local and global levels. The aim of this key discipline is to compare, describe and understand commonalities and differences in human living and thinking. In addition, in-depth concern with theories and methodologies provides students with critical qualifications enabling them to reflect on and analyze human practice in a global context. A key ability here is critical inquiry into the apparently universal nature of thought models, values ??and practices with a view to identifying the culture-specific origins that often spring from. Accordingly, the empirical methods involved in fieldwork and an engagement with the concept of culture are just as essential as familiarity with approaches of an anthropological / ethnological, societal or epistemological nature. The M.A. course that sets out to enhance students\' regional, theoretical and methodological knowledge as an indispensable basis enabling them to engage in independent academic work and devise problem-solving strategies of their own. The language of instruction is mostly German but many seminaries are also run in English to take account of the increasingly international complexion of the University.\r\n\r\nThe M.A. course in Anthropology (Ethnology) offers students:\r\n\r\nImmersion in essential theories in social and cultural anthropology (compulsory module PM 1); engagement with \"classical\" works on cultural anthropology is set in relation to present-day debts, theories and methods\r\n\r\nSpecialization in one or more theoretic preferences and / or one specific region (elective-compulsory modules WPM 2-3)\r\n\r\nOpportunities for individual or supervised research projects and the sound methodological training they involve (electrical-compulsory module WPM 4)\r\n\r\nOutstanding opportunities for acquisition of non-European (and European) languages ??(electrical-compulsory module WPM 5)\r\n\r\nPromotion of interdisciplinary skills, not least due to close contact with the Karl Jaspers Center for Advanced Tran cultural Studies and the South Asia Institute plus intensive connectivity with numerous neighboring disciplines (electrical-compulsory module WPM 5)\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Biosciences\r\nStudy options\r\nFull time (4 semesters)\r\nRegistration fees\r\n€ 3,000.00 (US $ 3,396) annually\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\n15 April 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nUniversity of Heidelberg\r\n\r\nSeminarstraße 2,\r\n\r\nHEIDELBERG,\r\n\r\nBaden Wurttemberg,\r\n\r\n69117, Germany\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents must have a Bachelor degree involving at least 4 years of full-time academic education.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nStudents who have, or expect to have, completed a relevant Bachelor\'s Degree (or equivalent) with an above-average grade by the end of the academic year preceding the required semester of entry.\r\n\r\nApplicants who native language is English, it is sufficient Proof that you have your university entrance qualification in one of the have acquainted these countries; Egypt - the certificate of a maximum of two years ago internationally recognized standardized English tests, eg. IELTS with one Overall grade of at least 7.0 points and at least 6.5 Each points in each subcategory, TOEFL IBT with one Score of at least 90 points and at least 22 Each point in each score of at least 185 points on the Cambridge English Scale'),
(19, 65, 'Master of Arts in English Studies ', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nContents of the study\r\n\r\nThe objectives of the master\'s program are to broaden and deepen the methodological and professional knowledge and skills acquired in undergraduate English-language study programs. The degree program English Studies is characterized by its strong research relevance and combines traditional literary and linguistic skills with skills in new cultural and mediation techniques. The students should be qualified equally for independent scientific work as well as for independent activities in linguistic, literary and information-oriented occupational fields.\r\n\r\nStructure of the study\r\n\r\nDuring the first three semesters, students complete four seminars, four lectures and two research-oriented, professionally supervised \"Independent Studies\" projects. Within these curricular guidelines, they can individually plan their study content and tailor it to their needs and interests. The annotated course catalog gives an insight into the thematic breadth of the course offer. During the fourth semester, students write the master\'s thesis and prepare for the oral exam.\r\n\r\nPossible occupational fields for graduates:\r\n\r\nUniversity career / doctorate\r\n\r\nEducational institutions / Adult education / Private schools in Germany and abroad\r\n\r\nTraining and coaching\r\n\r\nJournalism / Public Relations\r\n\r\nMuseums and archives\r\n\r\nTourism\r\n\r\nLecturer (culture, politics, economics)\r\n\r\nAdministration and in-house communication\r\n\r\nTranslation and publishing\r\n\r\nAdvertising\r\n\r\nInformation technology\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Modern Languages\r\nStudy options\r\nFull time (4 semesters)\r\nRegistration fees\r\n€ 3,000.00 (US $ 3,396) annually\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\n15 April 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nUniversity of Heidelberg\r\n\r\nSeminarstraße 2,\r\n\r\nHEIDELBERG,\r\n\r\nBaden Wurttemberg,\r\n\r\n69117, Germany\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents must have a Bachelor degree involving at least 4 years of full-time academic education.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nStudents who have, or expect to have, completed a relevant Bachelor\'s Degree (or equivalent) with an above-average grade by the end of the academic year preceding the required semester of entry.\r\n\r\nApplicants who native language is English, it is sufficient Proof that you have your university entrance qualification in one of the have acquainted these countries; Egypt - the certificate of a maximum of two years ago internationally recognized standardized English tests, eg. IELTS with one Overall grade of at least 7.0 points and at least 6.5 Each points in each subcategory, TOEFL IBT with one Score of at least 90 points and at least 22 Each point in each score of at least 185 points on the Cambridge English Scale'),
(20, 66, 'Master of Laws in United States Business', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nThe LL.M degree is for foreign lawyers. It is a one-year program, intended for students who have earned a foreign law degree and desire to augment their existing education with training in United States business law. The program is based on the existing concentration in Business Transactions, with the addition of an introductory course designed to introduce foreign-educated lawyers to the structure of the American legal system and the basics of U.S.. law.\r\n\r\nStudents must complete the following courses:\r\n\r\n    LAW 988 - The Structure and Operation of the American Legal System - 2 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 990 - Issues in the Law - 2 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 814 - Professional Responsibility - 3 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 818 - Fundamental Concepts of Income Taxation - 3 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 827 - Business Associations - 3 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 842 - Contract Drafting - 2 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 940 - Land Finance Law - 3 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 972 - Income Taxation of Business Organizations - 3 Credit Hours\r\n    LAW 841 - Secured Transactions - 3 Credit Hours\r\n\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nImage of Law\r\nStudy options\r\nFull time (24 credits)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nUS $ 46,356.00 annually\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\n21 August 2019, 8 January 2020\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nImage of Law\r\n\r\n1505 W. Cumberland Avenue,\r\n\r\nKNOXVILLE,\r\n\r\nTennessee,\r\n\r\n37996, United States\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents should have a TOEFL score of 550 on the paper-based test.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nApplicants must have obtained a bachelor\'s degree from a college or university accredited by the appropriate regional accreditation agency. A non-US. degree must be equivalent to a bachelor\'s degree from the United States and must be accredited by its regional or national accreditation agency. Applicants with non-US. degrees must have earned a minimum of 3.0 on a 4.0 scale or other equivalent to a \'B\' average. If you have completed previous graduate coursework, you must have earned a minimum of 3.3 out of a possible 4.0 GPA or other equivalent to a \'B +\' average.\r\n\r\nAn applicant requesting admission to the Graduate School may be required to submit results of the TOEFL or IELTS. Minimum score requirements for admission to the Graduate School are:\r\n\r\n    a total score of 80 on the internet-based TOEFL (iBT),\r\n    a 6.5 overall band score on the IELTS'),
(21, 67, 'American Studies (Including Year Abroad)', 'What will I learn?\r\nOur five-year BA American Studies (United States) (including foundation year and year abroad), will be suitable for you if your academic qualifications do not yet meet our entry requirements for the four-year version of this course and you want a program that increases your subject knowledge as well as improves your academic skills in order to support your academic performance. This five-year course includes a foundation year (Year Zero), followed by a further three years of study, plus a study abroad year or term. During your Year Zero, you study three academic subjects relevant to your chosen course as well as a compulsory academic skills module, with additional English language for non-English speakers. At Essex, we offer you an opportunity to understand some of the diversity and paradoxical aspects of the US through interdisciplinary studies. The US --haps more than any other society - lends itself to interdisciplinary study; its literature and film are connected to its policies, its cultures are linked to its histories. Crucially, you also spend either a term or a full academic year studying in the United States, so you can explore and become immersed in American culture.\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nEssex Pathways\r\nStudy options\r\nFull time with overseas time and foundation year (5 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nInformation not available\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nOctober 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nColchester Campus\r\n\r\nUniversity of Essex,\r\n\r\nWivenhoe Park,\r\n\r\nColchester,\r\n\r\nEssex,\r\n\r\nCO4 3SQ, England\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents need to have recognized high school qualifications and foundation programs for entry to the University'),
(21, 68, 'American Studies (Including Foundation Y', 'What will I learn?\r\nOur US BA studies for five years (including foundation year and year abroad) will be appropriate for you if your academic qualifications do not yet meet our admission requirements for this four-year course and you want a program that increases your knowledge of the subject and improves your skills Academy to support your academic performance. This five-year course includes the Foundation Year (Year 0), followed by another three years of study, as well as a year or semester study. During the year 0, you will study three academic subjects related to the course you have chosen in addition to the mandatory academic skills unit, with additional English for non-English speakers. In Essex, we offer you an opportunity to understand some of the diverse and contradictory aspects of the United States through interdisciplinary studies. The United States - perhaps more than any other society - is adapting to a multidisciplinary study. Her literature and film relate to her policy, and her culture is related to its history. Crucially, you are also spending a semester or a full academic year studying in the United States, so you can explore and indulge in American culture.\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nEssex Pathways\r\nStudy options\r\nFull time with overseas time and foundation year (5 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nInformation not available\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nOctober 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nColchester Campus\r\n\r\nUniversity of Essex,\r\n\r\nWevinhu Park,\r\n\r\nColchester,\r\n\r\nEssex,\r\n\r\nCO4 3SQ, England\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents must be qualified in high school and foundation programs to attend university'),
(22, 69, 'BA in History', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nFor a history major, curiosity is the largest prerequisite. You\'ll become an investigator into the minds, motivations, and movements that shaped our world, all while studying in one of the most historic cities on earth. Professors encourage classroom debate and rigorous research-you\'ll sharpen your analytical and critical-thinking skills to interpret the past, contextualize the present, and frame the future. You\'ll customize your studies by selecting a concentration in either United States History, Regional and Global Histories, or Public History. By graduation, you\'ll be ready for a career that requires you to ask challenging questions and provide well-articulated answers, from law to education to journalism to business.\r\n\r\nUnited States History\r\n\r\nChoose three of the following:\r\n· BLKST-226 The African American Experience in Literature and Film\r\n· BLKST-469 Research Seminar: African American Life in Slavery and Freedom- Reconstruction and the Freedman\'s Bureau\r\n· HST-227 Eyes on the Prize: Civil Rights Movement of the 20th Century\r\n· HST-271 African-American History 1619-1860\r\n· HST-272 African-American History From 1860\r\n· HST-288 Presidents We Love to Hate\r\n· HST-289 Hamilton: The Seminar\r\n· HST-29019th Century America\r\n· HST-292 American Foreign Relations Since 1898\r\n· HST-319 The History of Black Music in America\r\n· HST-333 The United States: 1898-1945\r\n· HST-334 The United States: 1945-1970\r\n· HST-335 The United States Since 1970\r\n· HST-361 Native America 1832 to Present\r\n· HST-363 Naval History: US. Constitution\r\n\r\n· HST-371 U.S. Women\'s History Colonial to 1865\r\n· HST-381 American Colonial History\r\n· HST-383 Boston: Heritage of a City\r\n· HST-389 Creating the Constitution\r\n\r\n· HST-394 Slavery in Film, Literature and History\r\n· HST-483 Death, Disease, Healing-Us HST\r\n· HST-494 Politics and Protest\r\n· UES-325 Environmental History of the US.\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nCollege of Arts and Sciences\r\nStudy options\r\nFull Time (MINIMUM OF 126 CREDITS)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nUS $ 38,420.00 annually\r\n\r\n* The price shown is indicative price, please contact with the university\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nSeptember 4, 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nCollege of Arts and Sciences\r\n\r\n73 Tremont Street,\r\n\r\nBOSTON,\r\n\r\nMassachusetts,\r\n\r\n02108, United States\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nStudents must have final high school transcript. English language requirements: TOEFL or IELTS score (TOEFL minimum is a 79, IELTS a 6.5); PTE-Academic with a minimum score of 54.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nStudents must have final high school transcript.\r\n\r\nEnglish language requirements\r\n\r\nTOEFL or IELTS score (TOEFL minimum is a 79, IELTS a 6.5)\r\n\r\nPTE-Academic with a minimum score of 54'),
(23, 70, 'Master of Arts in China Development Stud', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nThe dramatic social and economic transformation of China, one of the most populous and rapidly developing nations in the world, is a major historical event of the twenty century. In connection to this unparallel transformation, demand for knowledge of what is taking place in China and its global implications is greater than ever before.\r\n\r\nThe Master of Arts in China Development Studies [MAChDS] program emphasizes a comprehensive understanding of China through its global-local interactions and regional variations in politics, economy, trade, investment, environment, policy making, tourism and urban development. The prime objective is to educate students to become capable personnel for firms or institutions in both private and public sectors that have strong interest in China-related business and development.\r\n\r\nThe program provides an opportunity to local and international students for systematic training and independent research on development issues in contemporary China. The curriculum includes Chinese economies; international trade and foreign direct investment; China\'s cultural and urban development; climate change and environmental resources in China; public policies and regional development; China\'s environment and sustainable development; globalization and spatial economic transformation; cultural tourism; sustainable urban and transport planning; land governance and development and China field trip. Moreover, the curriculum has a capstone experience component that provides the students a platform to acquire research skills through completion of a dissertation or directed project under the supervision of a designated teacher. The Contemporary China Seminar Series is also an integral part of the program.\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Social Sciences\r\nStudy options\r\nFull Time (1 Year)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nHK $ 110,000.00 (US $ 14,014) per year\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nExpected September 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nThe University of Hong Kong\r\n\r\nG14, Ground Floor, Main Building,\r\n\r\nThe University of Hong Kong, Pokfulam,\r\n\r\nSouthern, Hong Kong, Hong Kong Island\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nApplicants shall hold a Bachelor\'s degree of this University or a qualification of equivalent standard from this University or another comparable institution accepted for this purpose; shall satisfy any other admission requirements which may be prescribed from time to time for the relevant curriculum. Other English Language Requirements accepted: an overall score of 550 or above (Paper-based test) in TOEFL; Egypt Grade C or above in Overseas General Certificate of Education (GCE); or Grade C in International General Certificate of Secondary Education (IGCSE); or Grade C in Cambridge Test of Proficiency in English Language (CPE).\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nApplicants will normally be required to hold a Bachelor\'s degree with honors of this University or a qualification of equivalent standard from this University or another university or comparable institution accepted for this purpose. Non-local students may only apply for the full-time mode.\r\n\r\nApplicants who is seeking admission on the basis of a qualification from a university or comparable institution outside Hong Kong of which the language of teaching and / or examination is not English is required to obtain:\r\n\r\n    a score of 550 or above in the paper-based Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) or a score of 213 in the computer-based TOEFL or a score of 80 in the internet based on TOEFL; Egypt\r\n    a minimum overall band of 6 with no subtest lower than 5.5 in the International English Language Testing System (IELTS); Egypt\r\n    Grade C or above in the Overseas General Certificate of Education (GCE); Egypt\r\n    Grade C or above in the International General Certificate of Secondary Education (IGCSE); Egypt\r\n    Grade C or above in the Cambridge Test of Proficiency in English Language'),
(25, 71, 'Bachelor of Engineering (Honours) in Ele', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nProgram Aims & Learning Outcomes\r\n\r\nThis program provides in-depth coverage of electrical engineering according to an income-based education philosophy. The program aims to produce engineers who are able to practice their profession in the broad area of ??electrical engineering which includes, but is not limited to, electrical power systems, energy conversion and utilization, transportation systems, environmental protection, control, computer and fiber- optical applications.\r\n\r\nA modern electrical engineer should possess a broad-based education and adequate specialist knowledge to undertake high-level work in design, planning, supervision and manufacturing. The program thus places emphasis on the mastery of fundamental principles and application of the latest engineering technology. Of equal importance is the training of leadership, entrepreneurship, and communication skills.\r\n\r\nWe encourage life-long learning so that graduates can keep abreast of new developments in engineering and technology.\r\n\r\nProgram Characteristics:\r\n\r\nThis program is a major electrical engineering degree program in Hong Kong, and provides unique and up-to-date education in the interesting field of electrical power and energy.\r\n\r\nThe curriculum is designed to give a balanced treatment of university core requirement, electrical engineering fundamentals, advanced and specialist subjects, and non-technical subjects such as economics and management.\r\n\r\nEngineering practice is an integrated component of the curriculum. Student learning is supplemented by a variety of laboratory, training and project activities. Students also develop good presentation and problem-solving skills through mini-projects and final-year projects. Students are required to take the Work-Integrated Education (WIE) component, which may be in the form of summer training or industrial attachment.\r\n\r\nProgram Structure\r\n\r\n    Students complete a first year of fundamental studies in common with students within the Engineering Broad Discipline. The Year One curriculum focuses on the underpinning subjects (such as Physics and Mathematics), languages, information technology, and General Education studies.\r\n    The Year Two curriculum focuses on the fundamentals of engineering science, engineering mathematics, computing, and introductory studies of electrical engineering.\r\n    In Year Three, students follow a semi-structured study pattern by taking compulsory core subjects in electrical engineering and Elective Subjects. The focus is on consolidating the fundamentals, team work and experimental methods. Beside, discipline-specific language subjects are studied.\r\n    Students take the advanced Core Subjects and Elective Subjects together with their Final Year Projects. Final Year Projects provide a comprehensive learning experience in engineering technology, problem-solving techniques, communication skills (both written and verbal) and creative thinking.\r\n\r\nCareer Prospects\r\n\r\nOur graduates have numerous employment opportunities in engineering planning and design, manufacturing, installation, maintenance and servicing, engineering sales and research.\r\n\r\nGraduates are able to develop rewarding professionals in major utility and transportation companies such as CLP Power Hong Kong Limited, the Hong kong Electric Company and the Mass Transit Railway Corporation. They are also employed by engineering consultant firms, contractor companies, international engineering enterprises, electrical product manufacturers, and the Government of the HKSAR (the Electrical and Mechanical Services Department, the Water Supplies Department, the Drainage Department and others).\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Engineering\r\nStudy options\r\nFull Time (4 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nHK $ 140,000.00 (US $ 17,836) per year\r\n\r\n* The price shown is indicative price, please contact with the university\r\nDeadline for registration\r\n\r\nExpected\r\n\r\nmore details\r\n\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\n2 September 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nThe Hong Kong Polytechnic University\r\n\r\nHung Hom,\r\n\r\nKowloon City, Hong Kong, Kowloon\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nApplicants must have a minimum score with at least Grade 4 in two Higher Level subjects. English Language Requirements: A Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) score of 80 for the Internet-based test or 550 for the paper-based test; An overall Band Score of 6 in the International English Language Testing System (IELTS); Grade C or above in GCEOL English; or Grade C / 4 or above in GCSE / IGCSE English.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nA High School (Graduation) Diploma and any one of the following:\r\n\r\n    a combined score of 1650 in the SAT Reasoning Test, with a sub-score of 8 on essay writing\r\n    a total score of 1190 in the Redesigned SAT Reasoning Test\r\n    an American College Test (ACT) composite score of 24\r\n    grade 3 in two Advanced Placement (AP) subjects\r\n\r\nGCE A-level / International A-level: Passes in 3 AL subjects OR 2 AL and 2 AS subjects;\r\n'),
(24, 72, 'Master of Science (MSc) in Global China ', '\r\n???? ??? ??????\r\n\r\nThe Master of Science (MSc) Program in Global China Studies is an interdisciplinary program which focuses on four broad subject areas, Economic and Social History, Comparative Humanities, Contemporary China, and Quantitative Social Analysis, providing students global and local perspectives on China’s past and present. It equips students with capacity building, especially capability of analysis, verbal communication and writing in a professional manner, for further study as well as to make a successful transition for future employment. In addition, the program is designed to enable advanced undergraduates from elite universities to take on the challenge of postgraduate study in Global China Studies and receive both a Bachelor’s and a Master’s degree in Global China Studies normally within four to five years.\r\n\r\nOn successful completion of the program, graduates will be able to:\r\n\r\n    Critically analyze significant social and cultural phenomena related to China and regarding China’s relations with the world;\r\n    Interpret events and developments in China\'s past and present from both global and local perspectives;\r\n    Effectively and appropriately communicate in written papers and reports in English to both non-expert and expert readers;\r\n    Persuasively and appropriately communicate when presenting and discussing with both non-expert and expert audiences and discussants; and\r\n    Carry out advanced research both independently and as part of a research team.\r\n\r\n?? ?? ??? ????\r\nSchool of Humanities and Social Science\r\n?????? ???????\r\n???? ???? (1 ??? )\r\n???? ?????????\r\nHK$120,000.00 (US$ 15,288) ??????\r\n\r\n* ????? ?????? ?? ??? ??????? ???? ????? ?? ???????\r\n????? ?????\r\n\r\n2 ?????? 2019\r\n???? ????? ??????\r\n\r\nHong Kong University of Science and Technology\r\n\r\nClear Water Bay,\r\n\r\nSai Kung, Hong Kong, Kowloon\r\n???? ??????\r\n?????? ?? ???\r\nApplicants should normally hold a Bachelor\'s degree for admission to a Taught Postgraduate degree programme; English Language Requirements: TOEFL - 550 (Paper-based), 79 (Internet-based); or IELTS (Academic): Overall Band at 6.5; or CET-6 (College English Test band 6): 450.\r\n?????? ????????\r\n\r\nApplicants seeking admission to a master\'s degree program should have obtained a bachelor’s degree from a recognized institution, or an approved equivalent qualification.\r\n\r\nProgram-Specific Admission Requirements\r\n\r\nA bachelor’s degree with a grade average of 3.0 out of 4.0; and\r\n\r\nOne of the following:\r\n\r\n    IELTS: 7.0 (all sub-scores: 5.5)\r\n    TOEFL pBT: 600\r\n    TOEFL iBT: 100\r\n    First language being English\r\n    Having obtained a bachelor’s degree awarded by an institution where the medium of instruction was English\r\n\r\nFor early admission of non-local applicants under nomination by strategic partner universities:\r\n\r\n    Having completed all the undergraduate coursework requirements with a cumulative grade average (CGA) of 3.0 out of 4.0; and\r\n    Having fulfilled the program-specific English language requirement specified above.\r\n\r\nAdditional Information\r\n\r\nApplicants who are HKUST graduates and have taken MGCS courses during their undergraduate studies may apply for transferring up to 12 of these credits to the MSc program upon admission.\r\n\r\nFor early admission of non-local applicants under nomination by strategic partner universities:\r\n\r\n    If admitted to the MSc program, students will remain registered as undergraduates in their home universities.\r\n    Upon completion of the MSc degree requirements, these students are required to submit an official copy of their bachelor’s degree certificate to the Program Office no later than 31 August each year in order to be conferred the MSc degree in Global China Studies at HKUST'),
(27, 73, 'Bachelor of Forestry Science (B.For.Sc)', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nThe Bachelor of Forestry Science (B. For. Sc.) Is one of the three undergraduate programs offered at the Faculty of Forestry since 1973. The objective of the program is to produce graduates who are professionally trained to assess, plan and manage forest resources as well as the implementation of various activities in the forestry sector. The graduates will be equipped with the knowledge and skills together with the use of current technology to efficiently manage forest resources based on the principles of sustainable forest management.\r\n\r\nCareer Opportunities\r\n\r\nAmong the job opportunities suitable are:\r\n\r\n    Forest Management\r\n    Forest Conservation\r\n    Plantation Management\r\n    Urban Forest Silviculture\r\n    Environmental Education\r\n    Forest Certification\r\n    Wood Utilization\r\n    Wildlife Management\r\n    Research and Development\r\n    Project Management\r\n    Business Development\r\n    Education\r\n\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Forestry\r\nStudy options\r\nFull Time (4 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nRM16,250.00 (US $ 3,991) per year\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nExpected February, September 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nUniversiti Putra Malaysia\r\n\r\nSERDANG,\r\n\r\nSelangor,\r\n\r\n43400, Malaysia\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nApplicant who is interested in pursuing his / her studied at UPM must fulfill the following: To have received a National Higher School Certificate (or an Advanced Level or the equivalent of 12 years of basic education) with the grade 80% and above. Egypt a Diploma from recognized Institutions with at least a CGPA of 3.00. English Language Requirements: IELTS - Minimum overall score of 6.0 for TESL / English or 5.5 for other programs; Egypt TOEFL - Minimum overall score of 550 for TESL / English or 500 for other programs; or Certified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - Certified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - enrolled at ELS-UPM - Level 109 English or Level 107 for other programs.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nStudents must have received a National Higher School Certificate (or an Advanced Level or the equivalent of 12 years of basic education) with the grade 80% and above or a Diploma from recognized institutions with at least a CGPA of 3.00. They also must have a minimum of Grade C (GP 2.00) at STPM level or its equivalent: in one (1) of the following subjects;\r\n\r\n    Biology;\r\n    Chemistry;\r\n    Physics;\r\n    Mathematics (T)\r\n\r\nEnglish Language requirement\r\n\r\nThey also must have\r\n\r\nIELTS - Minimum overall score of 6.0 for TESL / English or 5.5 for other programs; Egypt\r\n\r\nTOEFL - Minimum overall score of 550 for TESL / English or 500 for other programs; Egypt\r\n\r\nCertified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - Certified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - enrolled at ELS-UPM - Level 109 English or Level 107 for other programs'),
(26, 74, 'Bachelor of Landscape Architecture', 'What will I learn?\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\n\r\nBachelor of Landscape Architecture (BLA) program aims to train candidates to become landscape architects who are capable and skilful in all aspects of planning, designing and managing landscapes towards establishing a quality, healthy and balance environment for human needs.\r\n\r\nThe program is comprehensively designed so as to produce students who are well versed in their fields of specialization through multi-disciplinary courses. UPM\'s Landscape Architecture graduates are capable of facing current challenges in line with the Country\'s rapid development. They are sensitive and responsible in the utilization of natural resources to meet the country\'s development needs. Graduates from this program have found jobs in multi-national consultancy firms overseas.\r\n\r\nThis professional program is accredited by the Malaysian Public Services Department (JPA) and the Institute of Landscape Architects Malaysia (ILAM).\r\n\r\nProgram Outcomes\r\n\r\nProgram Objectives [Educational Objectives Program (PEO)] Bachelor of Landscape Architecture is to give: i. knowledgeable, skilled, creative and innovative landscape architects in the areas of assessment, planning, design, implementation and landscape management. ii. Ethical, architectural and professional landscape architects in the service of the community in terms of producing a working environment, safe and beautiful; and iii. Landscape architect who is sensitive and caring for national development needs and is capable of adjusting these requirements with the limitation of nature.\r\n\r\nCareer Information and Industrial Training\r\n\r\nThe National Landscape Policy (DLN) launched on 30 September 2011 is a holistic government direction in an effort to provide quality and sustainable living environment for the well-being of the people. DLN aims to make Malaysia the Most Beautiful Garden by 2020 which places the importance of landscape development as a necessity in the country\'s physical development and as a prerequisite for improving the quality of life and sustainability of a developed nation. In line with this ambition, the development of the national landscape should be planned, implemented, managed and regulated effectively. The Architecture Program of the Landscape Architecture offered is relevant and very necessary in realizing this policy. Through this program of study, the university can produce skilled graduations planning, designing, implementing and managing landscapes effectively. Beautiful, attractive and functioning landscapes for the purpose of providing them a constructive environment for all walks of life in line with the national mission of raising the level and sustainability of the quality of life of the community and towards making Malaysia a recognized and vibrant country of international status.\r\n\r\nIn which department am I?\r\nFaculty of Design and Architecture\r\nStudy options\r\nFull Time (4 years)\r\nRegistration fees\r\nRM16,250.00 (US $ 3,991) per year\r\nstarting date\r\n\r\nExpected February, September 2019\r\nPlace of the session\r\n\r\nUniversiti Putra Malaysia\r\n\r\nSERDANG,\r\n\r\nSelangor,\r\n\r\n43400, Malaysia\r\nAdmission requirements\r\nFor students from Egypt\r\nApplicant who is interested in pursuing his / her studied at UPM must fulfill the following: To have received a National Higher School Certificate (or an Advanced Level or the equivalent of 12 years of basic education) with the grade 80% and above. Egypt a Diploma from recognized Institutions with at least a CGPA of 3.00. English Language Requirements: IELTS - Minimum overall score of 6.0 for TESL / English or 5.5 for other programs; Egypt TOEFL - Minimum overall score of 550 for TESL / English or 500 for other programs; or Certified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - Certified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - enrolled at ELS-UPM - Level 109 English or Level 107 for other programs.\r\nFor international students\r\n\r\nStudents must have received a National Higher School Certificate (or an Advanced Level or the equivalent of 12 years of basic education) with the grade 80% and above or a Diploma from recognized institutions with at least a CGPA of 3.00.\r\n\r\nEnglish Language requirement\r\n\r\nThey also must have\r\n\r\nIELTS - Minimum overall score of 6.0 for TESL / English or 5.5 for other programs; Egypt\r\n\r\nTOEFL - Minimum overall score of 550 for TESL / English or 500 for other programs; Egypt\r\n\r\nCertified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - Certified Intensive English Program (CIEP) - enrolled at ELS-UPM - Level 109 English or Level 107 for other programs'),
(28, 75, 'Bachelor of Engineering (Hons) Civil Eng', '\r\n???? ??? ??????\r\n\r\nCivil engineering is the scientific study of the planning and construction of buildings, industrial infrastructures, roads and bridges. This programme concentrates on the practical application of technical knowledge (i.e. in mathematics and physical sciences, and their applications to all areas of civil engineering) to real-life and societal problems. Fieldwork is mainly related to planning, designing, constructing and maintaining public infrastructure or systems.\r\n\r\nIt aims to produce graduates who demonstrate capabilities to acquire and apply knowledge of science and engineering fundamentals, possess in-depth technical competence in the civil engineering discipline to undertake problem identification, formulation and solution, and possess the ability to utilise a systems approach to design and evaluate operational performance.\r\n\r\nCareer Prospects\r\n\r\nSite Engineer\r\n\r\nTraffic / Transportation Engineer\r\n\r\nStructure Engineer\r\n\r\nProject Engineer\r\n\r\nHydraulic Engineer\r\n\r\nGeotechnical Engineer\r\n?? ?? ??? ????\r\nLee Kong Chian Faculty of Engineering and Science\r\n?????? ???????\r\n???? ???? (4 ????? )\r\n???? ?????????\r\nRM16,300.00 (US$ 4,003) ??????\r\n\r\n* ????? ?????? ?? ??? ??????? ???? ????? ?? ???????\r\n????? ?????\r\n\r\n27 ??? 2019, 14 ?????? 2019\r\n???? ????? ??????\r\n\r\nSungai Long Campus\r\n\r\nJalan Sungai Long, Bandar Sungai Long,\r\n\r\nCheras,\r\n\r\nKAJANG,\r\n\r\nSelangor,\r\n\r\n43000, Malaysia\r\n???? ??????\r\n?????? ?? ???\r\nEntry with Standard Qualifications: UTAR welcomes applicants with any of the following qualifications for entry to Bachelor\'s Honours Degree Programme: Sijil Tinggi Persekolahan Malaysia (STPM); Unified Examination Certificate (UEC); A-Levels; South Australian Matriculation (SAM); Canadian Pre-University (CPU). Entry with Other Qualifications: Applicants with qualifications other than those described above, for example, a Diploma from a college/institution/polytechnic may also apply for admission to UTAR programmes. English Language Requirements: International English Language Testing System ( IELTS )-5.0; Paper-based TOEFL - 410; Internet-based Testing (iBT) - new TOEFL - 34; SPM English Language / O-level English Language- Credit; MUET - Band 3; UEC English Language - Grade B; Common European Framework of Reference for Languages (CEFR)- B1.\r\n?????? ????????\r\n\r\nAny foreign qualification that is equivalent to below given Malaysian qualifications is eligible for admission to this programme:\r\n\r\nSTPM with 2 principal passes in Mathematics and Physics or\r\n\r\nA-Level with 2 pass in Mathematics and Physics or\r\n\r\nSouth Australian Matriculation with an Australian Tertiary Admission Rank (ATAR) 70 and Grade B in Mathematics and Physics or\r\n\r\nCanadian Pre-University (CPU) with an average of 70% in 6 subjects in Mathematics and Physics\r\n\r\nOther equivalent qualifications recognised by the Malaysian Government\r\n\r\nEntry requirements may vary from country to country.\r\n\r\nThey also must have the following minimum score are as follows:\r\n\r\nInternational English Language Testing System (IELTS): 5.0\r\n\r\nInternet-based Testing (IBT) - TOEFL: 34\r\n\r\nPaper-based TOEFL: 410\r\n\r\nCambridge English: Advance (CAE) 160\r\n\r\nCambridge English: Proficiency (CPE) 180\r\n\r\nPearson Test of English (PTE) 36\r\n\r\nMUET: Band 3\r\n\r\nCommon European Framework of Reference for Languages (CEFR): B1\r\n\r\nSome Bachelor\' degree programmes may require higher English Language test scores as set by the Ministry of Higher Education (MOHE) or the Malaysian Qualificationsn Agency (MQA). These programmes are:\r\n\r\nBusiness: IELTS 5.5/TOEFL 550/equivalent (IELTS 6.0/equivalent for Finance)\r\n');
